European sailors first reached sub-Saharan Africa in 1442 when Portuguese ships arrived at the Senegal river. The Portuguese had been exploring the coasts of Morocco and Western Sahara since 1413, after they took over the Moroccan city of Ceuta [which is still a Spanish city today]. From 1413 to the 1440s, the Portuguese set up several fortified bases along the Moroccan coast, notably at Arzila, Mogador (now Essaouira), Safi, and Tangier. They maintained a strong presence in Morocco until 1578 when King Sebastião I of Portugal and many Portuguese nobles died at the Battle of Alcácer-Quibir. By 1471, leaders from West African regions between Senegal and Ghana had started trading and diplomatic relations with Portuguese merchants [key early trade locations included Gambia river, Bugendo on São Domingos river in Guinea-Bissau, and Sierra Leone].

For about 150 years following this period, West African rulers engaged mostly with Portuguese traders compared to other European nations. [There were also smaller missions by English and French traders but these occurred less often]. Initially, key motivations for the Portuguese were: 
1) Interest in large gold reserves found within Bono-Mansu and Akan territories;
2) Competition with Ottoman Empire for access to this gold [the Ottomans took Constantinople in 1453 causing concern across Christian Europe];
3) Desire to discover a sea route around Cape of Good Hope leading to markets in India;
4) Increasingly engaging in slave trade.

By the late-1590s Dutch traders began competing strongly against their Portuguese counterparts as major European merchants active within Africa due to larger ships carrying better quality goods. By mid-17th century Dutch forces captured significant former-Portuguese trading posts including Gorée (Senegal -1621), Elmina (Ghana -1637), Luanda (Angola -1641). Initially focused on textiles animal hides [for leather production], ivory; however by mid-century they too shifted towards slave trading which intensified post their capture during early-mid-1600s half Brazilian colonies from Portugal.
From then till about1654 Dutch controlled northern Brazil alongside its sugar plantations employing enslaved laborers; such colonial pursuits fueled further involvement into slave trade dominating latter part18th century.

As we move through second half17th century more European countries like Denmark England France Germany Sweden joined establishing various factories throughout West Africa deepening patterns seen African-European commerce interactions.

This chapter primarily explores initial phases pre-dominant slavery-focused trades examining events leading up till1650 followed by subsequent detailed examination transatlantic slave trades historical contexts thereafter.

European sailors first reached sub-Saharan Africa in 1442 when Portuguese ships arrived at the Senegal river. The Portuguese had been exploring the coasts of Morocco and Western Sahara since 1413, after they took over the Moroccan city of Ceuta [which is still a Spanish city today]. From 1413 to the 1440s, they set up several fortified bases along the Moroccan coast, notably at Arzila, Mogador (now Essaouira), Safi, and Tangier. They maintained a strong presence in Morocco until 1578 when King Sebastião I of Portugal and many Portuguese nobles died at the Battle of Alcácer-Quibir. By 1471, leaders from West African regions between Senegal and Ghana were trading and communicating with Portuguese merchants [key early trade locations included Gambia river, Bugendo on São Domingos river in Guinea-Bissau, and Sierra Leone].

For about 150 years following this period, West African rulers encountered Portuguese traders more frequently than those from any other European nation. [There were also smaller missions by English and French traders but these occurred less often]. Initially, key motivations for the Portuguese included: 
1) Interest in large gold reserves found within Bono-Mansu and Akan territories;
2) Competition with the Ottoman Empire for access to this gold [the Ottomans took Constantinople in 1453 causing concern across Christian Europe];
3) The aim to discover a sea route that would allow them to reach Indian markets via Cape of Good Hope;
4) Increasingly engaging in slave trade.

By the late-1590s Dutch traders began competing strongly against their Portuguese counterparts as leading European merchants in Africa due to larger ships carrying better quality goods. By mid-century Dutch forces had taken control over major former-Portuguese trading posts like Gorée Island (Senegal -1621), Elmina (Ghana -1637), Luanda (Angola -1641). Initially focused on textiles animal hides [for leather production], ivory; however by mid-17th century shifted focus towards slave trade which became prominent post their capture half Brazilian colonies during early-mid1600s where sugar plantations heavily relied on enslaved labor.

As we move into latter part of that century other European nations including Denmark England France Germany Sweden started establishing trading posts throughout West Africa deepening patterns seen previously regarding African-European commerce interactions.

This chapter primarily explores initial phases pre-dominance slave trade prior reaching year1650 followed detailed examination transatlantic slavery subsequent chapters.
